---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Header from "../../components/Header.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="OpenStack & OVN: Complete SDN Guide for Cloud Infrastructure | Kore.sh"
  description="A practical guide to Software Defined Networking with OpenStack and OVN: architecture, packet flow, operations, troubleshooting and production practices."
>
  <Header />

  <main class="pt-20">
    <article class="section pt-28 md:pt-40 max-w-4xl mx-auto">
      <header class="mb-12 text-center">
        <div
          class="flex items-center justify-center gap-4 text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mb-4"
        >
          <time datetime="2025-10-28">October 28, 2025</time>
          <span>•</span>
          <span>4 min read</span>
        </div>

        <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold mb-6">
          OpenStack & OVN: Complete SDN Guide
        </h1>

        <p class="text-xl text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mb-8">
          A practical explanation of how OpenStack Neutron, OVN and Open vSwitch
          work together to provide tenant networking, routing, security groups
          and production-grade troubleshooting paths.
        </p>

        <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 justify-center mb-8">
          {
            [
              "OpenStack",
              "OVN",
              "SDN",
              "Networking",
              "Cloud",
              "Infrastructure",
            ].map((tag) => <span class="tag">{tag}</span>)
          }
        </div>
      </header>

      <div class="prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
        <h2 id="introduction">Why OVN matters in OpenStack</h2>
        <p>
          OpenStack is modular by design. Nova manages compute, Cinder handles
          block storage, Keystone handles identity, and Neutron exposes
          Network-as-a-Service. Neutron is where virtual networks, subnets,
          routers, floating IPs and security groups become real infrastructure.
        </p>
        <p>
          In a private cloud, the network is often the hardest part to operate:
          thousands of virtual ports need isolation, routing, ACLs and external
          access, while the platform still has to remain debuggable during an
          incident. OVN, the Open Virtual Network project, modernizes this layer
          by making the network declarative and programmable.
        </p>

        <h2 id="sdn">The SDN model</h2>
        <p>
          Software Defined Networking separates the control plane from the data
          plane. The control plane decides what should happen to traffic. The
          data plane forwards packets as fast as possible. This separation makes
          the network programmable, observable and easier to automate.
        </p>

        <div class="overflow-x-auto my-6">
          <table class="min-w-full glass rounded-xl">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left">Plane</th>
                <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left">Role</th>
                <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left">Typical component</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-6 py-4"><strong>Control plane</strong></td>
                <td class="px-6 py-4"
                  >Computes routes, ACLs, logical switches and logical routers.</td
                >
                <td class="px-6 py-4">OVN Northbound / Southbound DBs</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-6 py-4"><strong>Data plane</strong></td>
                <td class="px-6 py-4"
                  >Applies flow rules and forwards packets on each hypervisor.</td
                >
                <td class="px-6 py-4">Open vSwitch kernel datapath</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-6 py-4"><strong>Application plane</strong></td>
                <td class="px-6 py-4"
                  >Receives user intent from APIs and orchestration systems.</td
                >
                <td class="px-6 py-4">OpenStack Neutron</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="ovs">Open vSwitch as the forwarding foundation</h2>
        <p>
          Open vSwitch runs on the hypervisors and provides virtual bridges. The
          integration bridge, often called <code>br-int</code>, connects virtual
          machine ports, router ports and tunnel interfaces. OVS applies flow
          rules that decide whether traffic should stay local, go through an
          overlay tunnel, hit a router pipeline or be dropped by an ACL.
        </p>
        <pre
          class="bg-gray-900 dark:bg-gray-800 text-gray-100 rounded-xl p-4 overflow-x-auto"><code># Inspect bridges, ports and interfaces
ovs-vsctl show

# Read OpenFlow entries on the integration bridge
ovs-ofctl dump-flows br-int

# Inspect datapath flows for a hot traffic path
ovs-appctl dpctl/dump-flows</code></pre>

        <h2 id="neutron">Neutron and OVN together</h2>
        <p>
          Neutron exposes the user-facing API. When a tenant creates a network,
          a subnet, a router or a security group, Neutron stores the desired
          state and passes it to the OVN mechanism driver. OVN translates that
          state into logical switches, logical routers, ports and ACLs.
        </p>
        <p>
          The OVN Northbound database stores the logical model. The Southbound
          database stores how this model is mapped to chassis, tunnels and
          datapath bindings. On each compute node, <code>ovn-controller</code>
          reads the Southbound state and programs OVS locally.
        </p>

        <h2 id="packet-flow">Typical packet flow</h2>
        <p>
          For east-west traffic, a packet leaves a VM through its tap interface,
          enters <code>br-int</code>, is matched by OVS flows, then is either
          delivered to another local port or encapsulated into a Geneve tunnel
          toward another hypervisor. For north-south traffic, the packet crosses
          logical router pipelines before reaching provider networking or a
          gateway node.
        </p>
        <pre
          class="bg-gray-900 dark:bg-gray-800 text-gray-100 rounded-xl p-4 overflow-x-auto"><code>VM tap
  -> br-int
  -> logical switch pipeline
  -> ACL / security group checks
  -> logical router pipeline
  -> Geneve tunnel or provider network
  -> remote chassis / gateway</code></pre>

        <h2 id="operations">Operational checks</h2>
        <p>
          In production, troubleshooting starts by checking whether the logical
          model is correct, whether OVN mapped it to the expected chassis, and
          whether OVS received the corresponding flows. The fastest path is to
          compare API state, OVN state and datapath state instead of guessing
          from symptoms only.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Check Neutron resources: networks, subnets, routers, ports.</li>
          <li>
            Check OVN Northbound objects: logical switches, routers, ACLs.
          </li>
          <li>
            Check OVN Southbound bindings: chassis, encaps, port bindings.
          </li>
          <li>Check OVS flows on the affected compute or gateway node.</li>
          <li>
            Validate MTU, Geneve tunnels, security group rules and routes.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="troubleshooting">Common failure patterns</h2>
        <p>
          Most incidents fall into a few categories: an instance port is bound
          to the wrong chassis, a security group blocks traffic, a route is
          missing, MTU is inconsistent across the overlay, or a gateway path is
          unhealthy. OVN helps because each layer can be inspected directly.
        </p>
        <pre
          class="bg-gray-900 dark:bg-gray-800 text-gray-100 rounded-xl p-4 overflow-x-auto"><code># Northbound logical state
ovn-nbctl show

# Southbound chassis and bindings
ovn-sbctl show
ovn-sbctl list Port_Binding

# Local OVS mapping
ovs-vsctl show
ovs-ofctl dump-flows br-int</code></pre>

        <h2 id="best-practices">Production practices</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Document the exact mapping between Neutron resources and OVN
            objects.
          </li>
          <li>
            Keep MTU values explicit across provider, overlay and guest
            networks.
          </li>
          <li>Monitor OVN databases, OVS processes and gateway nodes.</li>
          <li>
            Automate repetitive checks so incident response is consistent.
          </li>
          <li>
            Version operational runbooks with the same discipline as code.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="conclusion">Conclusion</h2>
        <p>
          OVN makes OpenStack networking more coherent by turning network intent
          into a logical model, then programming each hypervisor through Open
          vSwitch. The key to operating it well is to understand the chain:
          Neutron API, OVN databases, chassis bindings, OVS flows and packet
          path.
        </p>

        <div class="article-cta glass rounded-2xl p-6 mt-8">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">Questions or comments?</h3>
          <p class="mb-4">
            If you want to discuss OpenStack, OVN or private cloud networking,
            send a message through the contact form.
          </p>
          <a href="/#contact" class="button button--primary"
            >Contact via the secure form</a
          >
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>

<style>
  .prose {
    color: var(--color-text);
  }

  .prose h2 {
    font-size: 2rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    margin-top: 3rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    color: var(--color-heading);
  }

  .prose h3 {
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin-top: 2rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    color: var(--color-heading);
  }

  .prose p {
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.75;
  }

  .prose ul,
  .prose ol {
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    padding-left: 1.5rem;
  }

  .prose li {
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }

  .prose code {
    background: rgba(220, 38, 38, 0.1);
    padding: 0.2rem 0.4rem;
    border-radius: 0.25rem;
    font-size: 0.9em;
    color: var(--color-brand-red);
  }

  .prose pre code {
    background: transparent;
    padding: 0;
    color: inherit;
  }

  .prose table td,
  .prose table th {
    padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
  }

  .prose a.button--primary {
    color: var(--primary-foreground);
    text-decoration: none;
  }
</style>
